{"award_age":46.0,"bio_image":"full\/f3baee5c1f0bcd14d33c61fd1cac4772d1cc3fbd.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United Kingdom","date_of_birth":"1916-06-08T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2004-07-28T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/9\/99\/Francis_Crick_crop.jpg\/230px-Francis_Crick_crop.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Crick","mini_bio":"<p><b>Francis Harry Compton Crick<\/b>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Order_of_Merit_(Commonwealth)\" title=\"Order of Merit (Commonwealth)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">OM<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Royal_Society\" title=\"Royal Society\">FRS<\/a> (8 June 1916 \u2013 28 July 2004) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/British_people\" title=\"British people\">British<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Molecular_biology\" title=\"Molecular biology\">molecular biologist<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biophysics\" title=\"Biophysics\">biophysicist<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Neuroscience\" title=\"Neuroscience\">neuroscientist<\/a>, most noted for being a co-discoverer of the structure of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/DNA\" title=\"DNA\">DNA<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Molecule\" title=\"Molecule\">molecule<\/a> in 1953 with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/James_Watson\" title=\"James Watson\">James Watson<\/a>. Together with Watson and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Maurice_Wilkins\" title=\"Maurice Wilkins\">Maurice Wilkins<\/a>, he was jointly awarded the 1962 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_for_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine<\/a> \"for their discoveries concerning the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Molecular_geometry\" title=\"Molecular geometry\">molecular structure<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nucleic_acid\" title=\"Nucleic acid\">nucleic acids<\/a> and its significance for information transfer in living material\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Crick#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Obituary_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Crick#cite_note-Obituary-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Crick was an important theoretical <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Molecular_biology\" title=\"Molecular biology\">molecular biologist<\/a> and played a crucial role in research related to revealing the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genetic_code\" title=\"Genetic code\">genetic code<\/a>. He is widely known for use of the term \"<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Central_dogma_of_molecular_biology\" title=\"Central dogma of molecular biology\">central dogma<\/a>\" to summarize the idea that <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Gene\" title=\"Gene\">genetic<\/a> information flow in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cell_(biology)\" title=\"Cell (biology)\">cells<\/a> is essentially one-way, from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/DNA\" title=\"DNA\">DNA<\/a> to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/RNA\" title=\"RNA\">RNA<\/a> to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Protein\" title=\"Protein\">protein<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Crick#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>During the remainder of his career, he held the post of J.W. Kieckhefer Distinguished Research Professor at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Salk_Institute_for_Biological_Studies\" title=\"Salk Institute for Biological Studies\">Salk Institute for Biological Studies<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/La_Jolla,_California\" title=\"La Jolla, California\" class=\"mw-redirect\">La Jolla, California<\/a>. His later research centered on theoretical <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Neurobiology\" title=\"Neurobiology\" class=\"mw-redirect\">neurobiology<\/a> and attempts to advance the scientific study of human consciousness. He remained in this post until his death; \"he was editing a manuscript on his death bed, a scientist until the bitter end\" according to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Christof_Koch\" title=\"Christof Koch\">Christof Koch<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Crick#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Francis Crick","place_of_birth":"Weston Favell ,  Northamptonshire , England, UK","place_of_death":"San Diego ,  California , USA","text":"Francis Crick , Physiology or Medicine, 1962","year":1962.0}